My Gram Cracker passed away on December 8th, 2022. The last thing she ever did was make it to my wedding. It didn’t matter how many times we tried to tell her she should just stay home and rest, she was NOT going to miss it. Seeing her there meant so much to me, and I know it meant just as much to her. I can’t know for sure, but I think maybe she knew it was time. Maybe all she really wanted was to be surrounded by her family for a few more days. What I do know is I wish I would have squeezed her neck about 100 more times that weekend. These pictures will forever be priceless to me. 

She had possibly the happiest smile in the world. When I think of her, I think of two things.. Jesus & Joy. Those things have a lot in common don’t they?? I learned that from her. She truly believed everyday was a blessing, and you could tell. She believed in God’s plan whole heartedly, and I know that belief never wavered, even in her last moments. She died surrounded by all four of her daughters, just the way she would have wanted it. I am still learning what life’s like without her, but I am comforted by all the memories. Card games at the beach, listening to Meatloaf (her favorite band) in that old champagne colored Saturn she used to drive us around in (the kind with the seatbelts that automatically slid up when you closed the door), games of monopoly that lasted literal days, and Mexican Train dominoes at the kitchen table. She was known for making up her own rules, but the way she’d say them is what always got me. She’d say, “Commandment #82!.. Thou shalt NOT beat thy grandmother at dominoes!” Or, “Commandment #12!.. Thou shalt not make FUN of thy grandmother!” I’m smiling (and crying) typing this, because there were ALOT of commandments. Grammandments if you will.

She truly thought I could do anything. She loved hearing new songs (via burnt CD), and picking the ‘hits.’ I would say I lost one of my favorite cheerleaders that day, but that’s not true at all is it.. She’s still cheering. For me, and everyone else she loved so very well in her 87 years. I love you Gram Cracker, and I’m so thankful you spent the very last days of your life, being there for the best day of mine.

‘Biggest Fan’ is a love letter to my wife. She’s always telling me she’s MY biggest fan.. Well, this song is me making sure she knows I am hers too - even if she’s not the one on a stage every night. She’s been in my crowd long before there was even a crowd to be in, and she has believed in me through times I didn’t believe in myself. I know that kind of love isn’t easy to find, but I hope everybody out there looking for it finds it. Because in my opinion, we all need someone cheering us on in this crazy little game called life. We all need a ‘Biggest Fan.’ 🤍🎧 

It’s OUT NOW! Drop a comment if you’ve already listened and let me know if you’re a… Big fan of it… 😇 love y’all

Happy 31 to the love of my life. 31 years old and 31 weeks pregnant. I still can’t believe that either of those numbers are true 🥹

Mac has this little phrase she says all the time. She says “that’s happy” when something really makes her heart smile. Over the years, I have noticed that happy is kind of her word for love. I’ve always loved that about her. She relishes the simple, slow, seemingly mundane moments of life with the people that she loves. The longer I love her, the more I realize the “that’s happy” parts of life are what matter the most. She showed me that, and continues to. 

These photos are silly, but you see, she likes silly better than any perfect or polished ones. And while I hope all of you like them, I really just hope she looks at them and says, “that’s happy.”

I love you, baby. I hope today was your favorite kind of happy. @macdoleac 

-AD
